## 2. Step-by-step build order
1. In `orchestrator.py`, extract a single shared image-attach routine (used by both `/image` and auto-detect) so all attachment paths go through identical normalization and badge behavior.
2. Add a new helper in `orchestrator.py` that inspects paste payloads and returns an image path only when the payload is effectively a single path line (after trimming empty lines and drag/drop wrappers like quotes, ``& '...'``, `file:///`).
3. Update `_prompt_task()` first-line handling in `orchestrator.py` so `paste` is checked for single-image-path auto-attach before treating it as pasted text; on success, redraw prompt area and continue loop.
4. Update `_prompt_task()` continuation-line handling in `orchestrator.py` with the same paste-path auto-attach logic so drag/drop works consistently on follow-up lines too.
5. Keep `/image <path>` behavior in `orchestrator.py`, but route it through the shared attach routine to prevent divergence between manual command and drag/drop auto-flow.
6. Add tests in `tests/test_image_dragdrop_auto_attach.py` covering:
   - path cleaning for quoted and `& 'path'` forms,
   - single-line paste auto-attach success,
   - multi-line paste remains text attachment,
   - unsupported extension does not auto-attach.
7. Update `README.md` to explicitly state drag-and-drop image paths auto-attach to the top attachment menu without requiring `/image`.

## 3. Key technical decisions
1. Auto-attach only when pasted content resolves to one logical image path; any ambiguous/multi-line paste stays as text attachment to avoid false positives.
2. Use existing `_clean_path` + extension allowlist as the canonical validator; do not introduce a separate parsing rule-set.
3. Preserve `/image` as an explicit command, but unify internals so command and drag/drop always produce the same attachment state and rendering.
4. Apply the same detection rules in both primary and continuation prompt paths to eliminate inconsistent behavior across input modes.
